# C Programming Best Practices

## Project & File Structure

- Split code into **logical modules**: one `.h` + one `.c` per module
- Header files contain **declarations only** (function prototypes, typedefs, macro constants, structs); definitions go in `.c` files
- Wrap every header in an **include guard**:
  ```c
  #ifndef MODULE_NAME_H
  #define MODULE_NAME_H
  // ...
  #endif /* MODULE_NAME_H */
  ```
- Prefer `#pragma once` only when portability across all compilers is not required
- Keep includes minimal — include only what a translation unit actually uses

---

## Memory Management

- **Every `malloc`/`calloc`/`realloc` must be matched by exactly one `free`**
- Always check the return value of allocation functions — they can return `NULL`:
  ```c
  void *ptr = malloc(size);
  if (ptr == NULL) { /* handle error */ }
  ```
- Set pointers to `NULL` immediately after freeing them to prevent use-after-free bugs
- Prefer `calloc` over `malloc` when zero-initialisation is needed
- Use **RAII-style wrappers** or `goto cleanup` patterns to avoid leaks on error paths
- Never return a pointer to a local (stack) variable
- Avoid Variable Length Arrays (VLAs) for large or unknown sizes — use `malloc` instead

---

## Buffer & String Safety

- **Never use `gets()`** — it is removed from C11; use `fgets()` instead
- Prefer `snprintf` over `sprintf`; always pass the buffer size
- Use `strncpy` / `strncat` carefully — `strncpy` does **not** guarantee null-termination; ensure it manually or use safer alternatives (`strlcpy` where available)
- Validate all array indices before access; never assume input length
- Treat all external input (user, file, network) as **untrusted** and bounds-check it

---

## Pointers

- Initialise all pointers at declaration (`NULL` if not yet pointing at anything)
- Prefer `const T *` for read-only pointer parameters to communicate intent clearly
- Avoid **pointer arithmetic** beyond well-defined bounds (within the same array)
- Use `size_t` for sizes and indices, not `int` — it is the correct unsigned type for memory
- Document ownership: who allocates, who frees

---

## Types & Integer Safety

- Use **fixed-width types** from `<stdint.h>` (`uint8_t`, `int32_t`, etc.) when exact width matters (protocol packets, hardware registers)
- Use `size_t` / `ssize_t` for sizes and counts
- Be explicit about **signed vs. unsigned** comparisons — enable `-Wsign-compare` warning
- Check for integer overflow before arithmetic, especially in size calculations:
  ```c
  if (n > SIZE_MAX / sizeof(T)) { /* would overflow */ }
  ```
- Avoid implicit integer promotions in expressions mixing types

---

## Functions

- Functions do **one thing**; keep them short (≤ 40–50 lines as a guideline)
- Use `static` for **file-scope functions** not needed outside the translation unit
- Return error codes or use out-parameters for error signalling; document conventions in the header
- Limit function parameters to **≤ 4–5**; pass structs by pointer for more
- Mark read-only pointer parameters `const`:
  ```c
  void process(const Config *cfg, Buffer *out);
  ```

---

## Error Handling

- **Always check return values** of standard library and system calls (`fopen`, `malloc`, `read`, `write`, `pthread_*`, etc.)
- Define a consistent error-reporting strategy for the project (return codes, `errno`, or a custom error enum)
- Use `perror()` or `strerror(errno)` for descriptive OS-level error messages
- Clean up resources on every exit path — use `goto cleanup` for structured teardown:
  ```c
  FILE *f = fopen(...);
  if (!f) return ERR_IO;
  char *buf = malloc(...);
  if (!buf) { fclose(f); return ERR_MEM; }
  // ... work ...
  free(buf);
  fclose(f);
  return OK;
  ```

---

## Macros & Preprocessor

- Prefer **`enum` or `const` variables** over `#define` for named constants (typed, scoped, debuggable)
- Prefer **`inline` functions** over function-like macros to avoid side-effect pitfalls
- When macros are necessary, **wrap parameters and the whole body in parentheses**:
  ```c
  #define MAX(a, b) ((a) > (b) ? (a) : (b))
  ```
- Never use macros that evaluate arguments more than once if arguments may have side effects
- Use `do { ... } while (0)` for multi-statement macros

---

## Undefined & Implementation-Defined Behaviour

- Compile with **`-Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic`** and treat warnings as errors (`-Werror`)
- Enable sanitisers during development: **AddressSanitizer** (`-fsanitize=address`) and **UBSanitizer** (`-fsanitize=undefined`)
- Never rely on unspecified evaluation order of function arguments
- Avoid **signed integer overflow** — it is undefined behaviour in C
- Do not read from uninitialised variables
- Do not cast between incompatible pointer types (use `void *` as the generic pointer type)

---

## Naming & Style

- Functions and variables: `snake_case`
- Macros and constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Types / structs: `PascalCase_t` or `snake_case_t` — pick one and be consistent
- Prefix module-private symbols with the module name to simulate namespacing: `net_connect()`, `net_send()`
- Use **descriptive names** — avoid single-letter names outside tight loops (`i`, `j` are acceptable loop counters)

## Struct & Typedef

- Use `typedef` to hide struct implementation details when it improves readability, but expose the struct definition in the header if users need to allocate it on the stack
- Zero-initialise structs at declaration: `MyStruct s = {0};`

---

## Concurrency (POSIX Threads)

- Protect every shared variable with a `pthread_mutex_t`; document which mutex guards which data
- Always check `pthread_*` return values
- Avoid lock inversions — establish a consistent lock-acquisition order
- Prefer condition variables over busy-waiting / `sleep` polling

---

## Portability

- Write standard C (C11 or C17) unless platform extensions are explicitly required
- Use `#ifdef` guards to isolate platform-specific code
- Do not assume pointer size, struct padding, or endianness — use `sizeof`, `offsetof`, and serialisation helpers
- Test on both 32-bit and 64-bit targets when applicable
